    ///<param name="notifyDevices">Device needs to run the official Home Assistant app to receive notifications. If not specified, then all devices are used.</param>
    ///<param name="excludeNotifyDevices">Device needs to run the official Home Assistant app to receive notifications. If not specified, then all devices are used.</param>
    ///<param name="notifyHomeOrAway">With this option you can filter the devices based on their location.  • Select `Home` when you only want to notify those devices that are in the zone Home. • Select `Away` when you only want to notify those devices that are NOT in the zone Home. • Select `Both` when it does not matter where those devices are, they will be notified.  • Select `Prefer Home otherwise Away` when you need to notify those that are home, or when none the devices are home then notify those that are away. If not specified, then `Both` will be used. eg: Both</param>
    ///<param name="dataNotificationIcon">Change the default notification status bar icon to an mdi icon eg: mdi:motion-outline</param>
    ///<param name="dataNotificationColor">In Android you can set the color of the notification icon eg: [255,0,0]</param>
    ///<param name="notifyTitle">Notification title eg: Motion • Frontdoor</param>
    ///<param name="dataSubtitle">Subtitles and subjects are secondary headings eg: Subtitle goes here</param>
    ///<param name="notifyMessage">Notification message eg: There is somebody at the door!</param>
    ///<param name="notifyTts">Get your (Andriod) device to speak the notification. Use the notification message (`notify_message`), required when used with TTS. **NOTE** The Notification title (`notify_title`) will be ignored</param>
    ///<param name="notifyTtsInCar">Upgrade the notification message to a TTS message, when the `binary_sensor.###_android_auto` is `on`. This can be useful whilst driving with Android Auto that the notification that you are sending is announched via TTS. eg: true</param>
    ///<param name="dataGroup">Combine notification together visually. Custom values are allowed. eg: Motion</param>
    ///<param name="dataChannel">Notification channels allows users to separate their notifications easily (i.e. alarm vs laundry) so they can customize aspects like what type of sound is made and a lot of other device specific features. Devices running Android 8.0+ are able to create and manage notification channels on the fly using automations. Once a channel is created you can navigate to your notification settings and you will find the newly created channel, from there you can customize the behavior based on what your device allows. Custom values are allowed. eg: Motion</param>
    ///<param name="dataChannelRemove">If you wish to remove a channel. Depending on when you installed the app you may want to enable this option with the Notification channel (`data_channel`) `default` to clean up the old default channel *WARNING* The Notification Message (`notify_message`) will be ignored/overwritten. eg: True</param>
    ///<param name="dataTag">Replace an existing notification by using a tag for the notification. All subsequent notifications will take the place of a notification with the same tag. Custom values are allowed. eg: backyard-motion-detected</param>
    ///<param name="dataTagClearNotification">Removes the notification(s) with a certain tag (see Notification tag `data_tag`).  To remove/clear the persistent notification(s): Use Notification tag `data_tag: persistant`. *WARNING* The Notification Message (`notify_message`) will be ignored/overwritten. eg: True</param>
    ///<param name="dataAlertOnce">On Android you have the option for making a notification only alert once on the device.  This means it will only make a sound, vibrate and/or flash the LED once.  *WARNING* This must be used with a certain tag (see Notification tag `data_tag`). eg: True</param>
    ///<param name="dataImportance">Notifications will appear immediately in most cases. However, in some cases (such as phone being stationary or when screen has been turned off for prolonged period of time) and this is to override that default behavior eg: high</param>
    ///<param name="dataDeviceRing">Make the device ring even if on vibrate/silent ringer mode. Max will Only work for TTS messages eg: On</param>
    ///<param name="dataVisibility">How much of a notification is visible on the lock screen eg: public</param>
    ///<param name="dataSticky">Keep the notification from being dismissed when the user selects it eg: true</param>
    ///<param name="dataPersistent">Persistent notifications are notifications that cannot be dismissed by swiping away. It requires the Notification tag to be set. If not set it will set it to persistent. eg: true</param>
    ///<param name="dataTimeout">How many seconds a notification will be shown on a users device before being removed/dismissed automatically. eg: 120</param>
    ///<param name="dataChronometer">Shows a timestamp. Notification will not disappear when the timer reaches 0. Instead, it will continue decrementing into negative values. eg: &quot;{{now()+timedelta(minutes=1)}}&quot;</param>
    ///<param name="dataChronometerEnable">Show a count up/down timer. Notification will not disappear when the timer reaches 0. Instead, it will continue decrementing into negative values. eg: true</param>
